# Homework 4 help

todoList = [
    ['Walk the dog', 5],
    ['Do math homework', 9],
    ['Take a shower', 100],
    ['Do my Python hw', 200]
]

todoList.sort(key=lambda item: item[1])

# todoList.reverse()

counter = 0
# print(todoList)
print("Your todo list is:")
for todo in todoList:
#     print(todo)
    for field in todo:
        if counter % 2 == 0:
            print(field, end=", ")
        else:
            print("Priority: ", end="")
            print(field)
        counter = counter + 1
    print("\n")

File Input¶

Variables are a great way to store information. The problem with variables however is that the data does not persist. What happens when you store data into a variable but restart your program?

We can save our data to files on our system so later on we can access them. Let's open up the terminal and create a sample text file.

touch text-input.txt # creates a new file
echo "Hello World!" >> text-input.txt # adds the string to the text file
cat text-input.txt # displays the content of the text file

Now we'll be able to use the contents of that text file inside our program.

In [192]:
greeting = open('./data.txt')
print(greeting.read())
greeting.close()

5
hello world

read() allows us to read the all of the contents of a file into a single string. What if we wanted to separate the data?

Let's download this data file with stock data. Go back to your terminal and type in:

wget http://johnpham.net/cs190python/resources/NASDAQ100.csv

This file has the closing price per day going back to 1986. Let's create a program to find out what the largest delta was.

File Output¶

File output lets us store the data that our program creates into files. Those files can then be used in our program later or in other programs.

In [207]:
# (filename, mode)
outFile = open("file.txt", "w")
outFile.write("This is a filejkdfdfkjglsdkfghgkjdfgk I just made\n")
outFile.close()

inFile = open("file.txt")
print(inFile.read())
inFile.close()

# outFile = open("bobo.txt", "w")
# outFile.write("I'm feeling kind of hungry\n")
# outFile.close()

# inFile = open("bobo.txt")
# print(inFile.read())
# inFile.close()

# What happened to the first thing we wrote?

This is a filejkdfdfkjglsdkfghgkjdfgk I just made

Using APIs with Requests¶

So far we've been downloading data through our terminal. That's an extra step that we don't need to do. We requests, we can download data directly from our program.

In [208]:
import requests

rawData = requests.get('http://johnpham.net/cs190python/resources/NASDAQ100.csv')
print(rawData.text)

# This does not create a new file unlike before. The data is stored in your program's memory

JSON¶

JSON is a way to organize data. It provides a uniform structure for us to work with.

In [221]:
import requests
from IPython.core.display import display, HTML

gif = requests.get('https://api.giphy.com/v1/gifs/random?api_key=c6caa15f718f4a64859883c625d3d5ea&tag=&rating=G')

print(gif.json()['data']['image_original_url'])
imgURL = gif.json()['data']['image_original_url']
imgTag = "<img src='{}'/>".format(imgURL)
display(HTML(imgTag))

Introduction to Matplotlib¶

So we have all of this data. That's great and all but how can we get useful information out of it? Pictures are a great way to do so!

Let's graph the NASDAQ data.

In [231]:
# allows you to display charts within the notebook
%matplotlib inline

import matplotlib as mpl
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

bobo = [0, 1, 2, 3, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10]
anna = [-50, 2, 5, 5, 8, 100, 20, -30, 7, 10]

plt.plot(bobo, anna)
plt.ylabel('Cash Flow $$$')
plt.xlabel('Time (hdays)')
plt.show()
In [149]:
import datetime
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.dates as mdates
import matplotlib.cbook as cbook

years = mdates.YearLocator()   # every year
months = mdates.MonthLocator()  # every month
yearsFmt = mdates.DateFormatter('%Y')

# Load a numpy record array from yahoo csv data with fields date, open, close,
# volume, adj_close from the mpl-data/example directory. The record array
# stores the date as an np.datetime64 with a day unit ('D') in the date column.
with cbook.get_sample_data('goog.npz') as datafile:
    r = np.load(datafile)['price_data'].view(np.recarray)
# Matplotlib works better with datetime.datetime than np.datetime64, but the
# latter is more portable.
date = r.date.astype('O')

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(date, r.adj_close)


# format the ticks
ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(years)
ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(yearsFmt)
ax.xaxis.set_minor_locator(months)

datemin = datetime.date(date.min().year, 1, 1)
datemax = datetime.date(date.max().year + 1, 1, 1)
ax.set_xlim(datemin, datemax)


# format the coords message box
def price(x):
    return '$%1.2f' % x
ax.format_xdata = mdates.DateFormatter('%Y-%m-%d')
ax.format_ydata = price
ax.grid(True)

# rotates and right aligns the x labels, and moves the bottom of the
# axes up to make room for them
fig.autofmt_xdate()

plt.show()
In [232]:
# allows you to display charts within the notebook
%matplotlib inline

import matplotlib
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

dates = []
prices = []

data = open('NASDAQ100.csv').read().split(',')

# print(data)

counter = 0
for item in data:
    if counter % 2 == 0:
        dates.append(item)
    else:
        prices.append(item)
    counter += 1

dates.pop()
plt.plot(dates[:100], prices[:100], label='prices')
plt.show()
# print(len(dates), len(prices))
# print(dates)

Homework 5¶

  1. Create a new notebook naming it [netid]_[homework5]. An example of this is jpham035_homework5.

  2. Create a Markdown cell with the following information:

    • A title
    • Your name
    • Your email

  3. Create a program that manages allows many users to input their name and age. Once the users have signaled that they're done doing input, you will write the data to a text file.

  4. Each person will also be randomly assigned a code name. You will be using this api: http://names.drycodes.com/1?nameOptions=all to get a random name.
